1. Use a loop to print out the numbers 1 to 12 in one line (you may have to remind the student how to use System.out.print(). Then, print out the multiples of 2 up to 24 in one line. Then, print out all the multiples of 3 up to 36 in one line.
2. What if we wanted to print out all of the multiples, up to 12? Explain to the student how we can nest for loops inside each other. Use a nested for loop to print the 12x12 multiplication table. What would we have to change to print the 20x20 multiplication table?
3. Use nested loops to print out this pattern:
*
**
***
****
*****

4. Use nested loops to print out the pattern in reverse:
*****
****
***
**
*

5. Use nested loops (and conditionals!) to print out this pattern:
*----
-*---
--*--
---*-
----*



class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Multiplication table
    for (int i = 1; i <= 12; i++) {
      for (int j = 1; j <= 12; j++) {
        System.out.print(i*j + " ");
      }
      System.out.println();
    }

    // Star pattern
    for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
      for (int j = 1; j <= i; j++) {
        System.out.print("*");
      }
      System.out.println();
    }

    for (int i = 5; i >= 1; i--) {
      for (int j = 1; j <= i; j++) {
        System.out.print("*");
      }
      System.out.println();
    }

    // Diagonal pattern
    for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
      for (int j = 0; j < 5; j++) {
        if (i == j) {
          System.out.print("*");
        } else {
          System.out.print("-");
        }
      }
      System.out.println();
    }
  }
}
